{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508575"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:06:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:06:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2808"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2808"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.22,0.11,0.04,0.57]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2785"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41886"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2785"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2808"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26858"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3733"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3785"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42569"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41886"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department by ambulance after being found by his sister unconscious. He was found surrounded by vomit in his bathroom soon after taking a large number of pills. Collateral history from his sister reveals a medical history of depression, chronic back pain and migraines. His medications list includes fluoxetine, amitriptyline, paracetamol, oxycodone, propranolol and occasional sumatriptan. He does not drink alcohol, is a lifelong non-smoker and uses no recreational drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he is drowsy but alert to voice. His pulse rate is 134/min, blood pressure 99/57 mmHg, respiratory rate 11/min, SpO2 99% on room air and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. On neurological examination he is able to move all four limbs on command, his pupils are responsive to light and dilated bilaterally. There is no evidence of mechanical injury. His peripheries are warm to the touch. His blood glucose level is 5.2 mmol/L (3.2 \u2013 5.5 mmol/L). His ECG is shown below (Image). \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is he most likely to have taken an overdose of?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paracetamol","Fluoxetine","Oxycodone","Propanolol","Amitriptyline"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation is consistent with tricyclic antidepressant (TCA) overdose, hence \u003Cstrong\u003Eamitriptyline\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer. TCA overdose leads to anticholinergic effects (mydriasis, dry tongue, urinary retention, warm skin), cardiac effects (sinus tachycardia, hypotension, vasodilatation) and neurological effects (drowsiness, coma, seizures). The ECG shows a sinus tachycardia and borderline QT prolongation, consistent with TCA overdose. Other potential TCA induced changes include QRS widening, positive R waves in aVR, PR prolongation and heart block.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol\u003C/strong\u003E toxicity presents in the acute phase with abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting and diaphoresis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluoxetine\u003C/strong\u003E is a selective serotonin re-uptake inhibitor (SSRI), and acute overdose may cause a short period of tremor, nausea, vomiting, tachycardia and drowsiness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxycodone\u003C/strong\u003E is an opioid analgesic. Toxicity causes altered conscious state, respiratory depression and constricted pupils.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropanolol\u003C/strong\u003E is a beta-blocker, toxicity with this agent would cause bradycardia rather than tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cardiotoxicity secondary to TCA overdose is caused by blockade of cardiac sodium channels and can be fatal."],"references":["Kerr GW, McGuffie AC, Wilkie S. Tricyclic antidepressant overdose: a review. Emerg Med J. 2001;18(4):236-41. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1725608/","Thanacoody HK, Thomas SH. Tricyclic antidepressant poisoning: cardiovascular toxicity. Toxicol Rev. 2005;24(3):205-14. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16390222/#:~:text=Tricyclic%20antidepressants%20remain%20a%20common,be%20particularly%20toxic%20in%20overdose."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26858"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2808"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"11610"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"11610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/11610"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/424628af-fb7a-49c0-85d0-288007dd02c6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/424628af-fb7a-49c0-85d0-288007dd02c6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":414}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26858"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-25T21:56:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-25T21:56:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2785"}},"content":